Performance of jpeglib¶

This notebook contains a short performance evaluation of jpeglib library.

Outcome:

  • In compression jpeglib outperforms cv2 and pillow. In decompression, jpeglib is faster than pillow, but performs similar to cv2.
  • torchjpeg is faster in DCT reading than jpeglib, they are comparable in DCT writing.

Experiments supporting the conclusion above used libjpeg, however measurements of performance using libjpeg-turbo were carried out as well.

The timer class is implemented as an internal module of jpeglib already.

In [3]:
# timer
import logging
logging.basicConfig(level=logging.WARNING)
from jpeglib import Timer

The DCT reading and writing are compared with torchjpeg library. The compression and decompression from and to RGB spatial domain is compared with pillow library.

For each of the four procedures, there are four test cases performed based on the processed image size.

  • $64\times 64$
  • $256\times 256$
  • $1024\times 1024$
  • $2048\times 2048$

DCT reading¶

Setup procedure used in DCT reading randomly generates image spatial representation and saves it into the tmp directory.

In [4]:
# generate random image (RGB)
import numpy as np
def generate_random_image(shape=(512,512)):
    return np.random.randint(0,255,(*shape,3))
def create_random_image_file(shape=(512,512)):
    x = generate_random_image(shape=shape)
    im = PIL.Image.fromarray(x.astype('uint8'), 'RGB')
    im.save('../tmp/image.jpg')

Next, we define the measurement of the libraries in reading of DCT as repetitive generating of random image and timed reading.

In [5]:
import pandas as pd
def measure_dct_reading(shape, N=100):
    t_tj,t_tj_np,t_jl,t_jl_turbo = [],[],[],[]
    for i in range(N):
        
        # measure torchjpeg
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        t1 = Timer("torchjpeg")
        dimensions, qt, Y, CbCr = torchjpeg.codec.read_coefficients("../tmp/image.jpg")
        t1.stop()
        t_tj.append(t1.time)
        
        # measure torchjpeg with numpy conversion
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        t2 = Timer("torchjpeg w/.to_numpy()")
        dimensions, qt, Y, CbCr = torchjpeg.codec.read_coefficients("../tmp/image.jpg")
        qt   = qt.numpy()
        Y    = np.einsum('abcde->acbed', Y.numpy())
        CbCr = np.einsum('bcde->cbed', CbCr[0].numpy())
        t2.stop()
        t_tj_np.append(t2.time)
        
        # jpeglib
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('6b')
        t3 = Timer("jpeglib")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG("../tmp/image.jpg")
        Y,CbCr,qt = im.read_dct()
        t3.stop()
        t_jl.append(t3.time)
        
        # jpeglib w/SIMD acceleration
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('turbo210')
        t4 = Timer("jpeglib (turbo)")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG("../tmp/image.jpg")
        Y,CbCr,qt = im.read_dct()
        t4.stop()
        t_jl_turbo.append(t4.time)
    
    # collect the measurements into dataframe
    return pd.concat([
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'torchjpeg', 'time': t_tj}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'torchjpeg+to_numpy()', 'time': t_tj_np}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib', 'time': t_jl}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib (turbo)', 'time': t_jl_turbo})
    ], ignore_index=True)

The results of the DCT reading in the four test cases are

sns.kdeplot(data=t64, x="time", hue="library").set_title("DCT reading of image 64x64");

DCT writing¶

DCT writing randomly generates luminance and chrominance matrices of DCT coefficients.

In [10]:
# generate random Y/CbCr
import torch
def generate_random_YCbCr(shape=(512,512)):
    Y = np.random.randint(0,128,(1,int(shape[0]/8),int(shape[1]/8),8,8)).astype(np.int16)
    CbCr = np.random.randint(-63,63,(2,int(shape[0]/8/2),int(shape[1]/8/2),8,8)).astype(np.int16)
    return Y,CbCr
def generate_random_YCbCr_torch(shape=(512,512)):
    Y,CbCr = generate_random_YCbCr(shape=shape)
    return torch.from_numpy(Y),torch.from_numpy(CbCr)

API of torchjpeg requires specification of quantization matrix. The standard matrix for quality 50 is used.

In [11]:

     [99,99,99,99,99,99,99,99]]
]).to(torch.int16)
qt50_np = qt50.numpy()[:2]

The measurement of the DCT writing is similar to reading - we repeatedly generate random DCT coefficients and measure the time the writing takes.

In [12]:
def measure_dct_writing(shape, N=100):
    t_tj,t_tj_np,t_jl,t_jl_turbo = [],[],[],[]
    dimensions = torch.Tensor([
        [shape[0],shape[1]],
        [shape[0]/2,shape[1]/2],
        [shape[0]/2,shape[1]/2]
    ]).to(torch.int32)
    for i in range(N):
        
        # measure torchjpeg
        Y,CbCr = generate_random_YCbCr_torch(shape)
        t1 = Timer("torchjpeg")
        torchjpeg.codec.write_coefficients('../tmp/image.jpg', dimensions, qt50, Y, CbCr)
        t1.stop()
        t_tj.append(t1.time)
        
        # measure torchjpeg with numpy conversion
        Y,CbCr = generate_random_YCbCr(shape)
        t2 = Timer("torchjpeg w/.from_numpy()")
        Y,CbCr = torch.from_numpy(Y),torch.from_numpy(CbCr)
        torchjpeg.codec.write_coefficients("../tmp/image.jpg", dimensions, qt50, Y, CbCr)
        t2.stop()
        t_tj_np.append(t2.time)
        
        # jpeglib
        Y,CbCr = generate_random_YCbCr(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('6b')
        t3 = Timer("jpeglib")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG()
        im.write_dct("../tmp/image.jpg", Y, CbCr, qt50_np)
        t3.stop()
        t_jl.append(t3.time)
        
        # jpeglib w/SIMD acceleration
        Y,CbCr = generate_random_YCbCr(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('turbo210')
        t4 = Timer("jpeglib (turbo)")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG()
        im.write_dct("../tmp/image.jpg", Y, CbCr, qt50_np)
        t4.stop()
        t_jl_turbo.append(t4.time)
        
    df = pd.concat([
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'torchjpeg', 'time': t_tj}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'torchjpeg+to_numpy()', 'time': t_tj_np}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib', 'time': t_jl}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib (turbo)', 'time': t_jl_turbo})
    ], ignore_index=True)
    return df

Test cases for writing of DCT coefficients differ based on image shapes

  • $64\times 64$
  • $256\times 256$
  • $1024\times 1024$
  • $2048\times 2048$

For DCT writing, jpeglib and torchjpeg perform comparably. When using SIMD acceleration, jpeglib is faster.

JPEG decompression¶

Next is the performance comparison in JPEG decompression between jpeglib and pillow, i.e. reading of JPEG file as RGB spatial domain.

In [17]:
def measure_spatial_reading(shape, N=100):
    t_pil,t_cv2,t_jl,t_jl_turbo = [],[],[],[]
    for i in range(N):
        
        # PIL
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        t1 = Timer("pillow")
        x = np.array(PIL.Image.open("../tmp/image.jpg"))
        t1.stop()
        t_pil.append(t1.time)
        
        # cv2
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        t2 = Timer("cv2")
        x = cv2.imread("../tmp/image.jpg")
        t2.stop()
        t_cv2.append(t2.time)

        # jpeglib
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('6b')
        t3 = Timer("jpeglib")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG("../tmp/image.jpg")
        Y,CbCr,qt = im.read_dct()
        t3.stop()
        t_jl.append(t3.time)
        
        # jpeglib w/SIMD acceleration
        create_random_image_file(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('turbo210')
        t4 = Timer("jpeglib (turbo)")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG("../tmp/image.jpg")
        Y,CbCr,qt = im.read_dct()
        t4.stop()
        t_jl_turbo.append(t4.time)
    
    # collect the measurements into dataframe
    return pd.concat([
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'PIL', 'time': t_pil}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'cv2', 'time': t_cv2}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib', 'time': t_jl}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib (turbo)', 'time': t_jl_turbo})
    ], ignore_index=True)

JPEG compression¶

Next is the performance comparison in JPEG compression between jpeglib and pillow, i.e. writing RGB spatial domain to JPEG file.

In [22]:
def measure_spatial_writing(shape, N=100):
    t_pil,t_cv2,t_jl,t_jl_turbo = [],[],[],[]
    for i in range(N):
        
        # PIL
        x = generate_random_image(shape)
        t1 = Timer("pillow")
        im = PIL.Image.fromarray(x.astype('uint8'), 'RGB')
        im.save("../tmp/image.jpg")
        t1.stop()
        t_pil.append(t1.time)
        
        # cv2
        x = generate_random_image(shape)
        t2 = Timer("cv2")
        x = cv2.imwrite("../tmp/image.jpg", x)
        t2.stop()
        t_cv2.append(t2.time)

        # jpeglib
        x = generate_random_image(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('6b')
        t3 = Timer("jpeglib")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG()
        im.write_spatial("../tmp/image.jpg", x)
        t3.stop()
        t_jl.append(t3.time)
        
        # jpeglib w/SIMD acceleration
        generate_random_image(shape)
        jpeglib.version.set('turbo210')
        t4 = Timer("jpeglib (turbo)")
        im = jpeglib.JPEG()
        im.write_spatial("../tmp/image.jpg", x)
        t4.stop()
        t_jl_turbo.append(t4.time)
    
    # collect the measurements into dataframe
    return pd.concat([
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'PIL', 'time': t_pil}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'cv2', 'time': t_cv2}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib', 'time': t_jl}),
        pd.DataFrame({'library': 'jpeglib (turbo)', 'time': t_jl_turbo})
    ], ignore_index=True)
